$(
=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
        Ratio test for infinite series convergence
=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
$)


  ${
    $d k n A $.  $d k n F $.  $d k M $.  $d k n N $.  $d k n ph $.  $d k n W $.
    $d k n Z $.
    cvgrat.1 $e |- Z = ( ZZ>= ` M ) $.
    cvgrat.2 $e |- W = ( ZZ>= ` N ) $.
    cvgrat.3 $e |- ( ph -> A e. RR ) $.
    cvgrat.4 $e |- ( ph -> A < 1 ) $.
    cvgrat.5 $e |- ( ph -> N e. Z ) $.
    cvgrat.6 $e |- ( ( ph /\ k e. Z ) -> ( F ` k ) e. CC ) $.
    cvgrat.7 $e |- ( ( ph /\ k e. W ) ->
               ( abs ` ( F ` ( k + 1 ) ) ) <_ ( A x. ( abs ` ( F ` k ) ) ) ) $.
    $( Ratio test for convergence of a complex infinite series.  If the ratio
       ` A ` of the absolute values of of successive terms in an infinite
       sequence ` F ` is less than 1 for all terms beyond some index ` B ` ,
       then the infinite sum of the terms of ` F ` converges to a complex
       number.  Equivalent to first part of Exercise 4 of [Gleason] p. 182.
       (The proof was shortened by Mario Carneiro, 27-Apr-2014.) $)
    cvgrat $p |- ( ph -> seq M ( + , F ) e. dom ~~> ) $=
